VPC Peering: 
â€¢	A VPC peering connection is a networking connection between two VPCs that enables you to route traffic between them using private IPv4 addresses or IPv6 addresses. 
â€¢	Instances in either VPC can communicate with each other as if they are within the same network.
â€¢	You can create a VPC peering connection between your own VPCs, or with a VPC in another AWS account.
â€¢	The VPCs can be in different regions (also known as an inter-region VPC peering connection
Conditions:
â€¢	CIDR block shouldnâ€™t overlap 
â€¢	Transitive peering relationships are not supported. i.e here VPC B cannot connect with VPC C.
â€¢	If the VPCs are in different regions, inter-region data transfer costs apply.
â€¢	You cannot have more than one VPC peering connection between the same two VPCs at the same time.

Elastic load Balancer (ELB):

	Manage and control the flow of inbound request to group of targets by distributing the requests evenly across the targets. The targets may be EC2 instances lambda or containers
Types of Load balancer:

Application load balancer:
â€¢	Used mainly for web application running http and https protocols.
â€¢	Operates at request level.

Network Load balancer:
â€¢	Ultra-high Performance at very low latency.
â€¢	Operates at connection level, routing traffic to targets with in VPC.
â€¢	Can handle millions of requests per second.

Classic load Balancer:
â€¢	Used for applications that were built in existing EC2 classic env.
â€¢	Operates both at connection & request level.

